Since you need **three** themes (not just light/dark), use the **ResourceDictionary swap** approach. `AppThemeBinding` only supports two themes, so it won't work here.

## Setup

### 1. Create three theme dictionaries with matching keys

**Themes/LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#333333</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#2196F3</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/DarkTheme.xaml** ŌĆö same keys, dark values.

**Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml** ŌĆö same keys, high-contrast values (e.g., `Black` background, `White` text, `Yellow` accent).

Each needs a code-behind calling `InitializeComponent()`:

```csharp
namespace MyApp.Themes;
public partial class LightTheme : ResourceDictionary
{
    public LightTheme() => InitializeComponent();
}
```

### 2. Use `DynamicResource` everywhere (not `StaticResource`)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackgroundColor}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
    <Button Text="Go" BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 3. Create a theme-switching helper

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        var mergedDictionaries = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        mergedDictionaries.Clear();
        mergedDictionaries.Add(themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme()
        });

        // Persist choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

### 4. Settings page ŌĆö apply immediately on selection

```csharp
void OnThemePicked(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    string selected = themePicker.SelectedItem as string; // "Light", "Dark", "HighContrast"
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(selected);
}
```

### 5. Restore on startup (App constructor)

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
}
```

### 6. Android: ensure `ConfigChanges.UiMode` is set

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, include `ConfigChanges.UiMode` in the `[Activity]` attribute to prevent activity restarts on theme changes.

## Key rules

| Rule | Why |
|------|-----|
| Use `DynamicResource`, never `StaticResource` | Static bindings freeze at load and won't update |
| Every `x:Key` must exist in all three dictionaries | Missing keys silently fall back to defaults |
| No hardcoded colors on themed elements | They bypass the dictionary entirely |

This gives you immediate, app-wide theme switching driven entirely by user preference.
